<FIRST>u i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0484 02-18 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Young Israeli Stabbed In Arab East Jerusalem</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with detail, background. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab assailants today ambushed two Jewish
seminary students near the old Walled City in Arab east Jerusalem
and stabbed one of them to death in what authorities described as a
terrorist attack.
   Shlomi Cohen, 21, was stabbed in the heart with a pocket knife in
the afternoon while he and a friend walked outside the Old City wall
near Zion Gate on Mount Zion in Arab East Jerusalem, said police
spokesman Uzi Sandori.
   Cohen struggled briefly with his assailant after the stabbing,
ran a few yards, collapsed and died, Sandori said.
   When reporters arrived at the scene, Cohen was lying on the
ground, his body covered by a blood-stained white sheet.
   ``This seems to be a terrorist attack,'' said Jerusalem police
commander Yosef Yehudai.
   Israel Army radio said the assailant and several accomplices fled
into the narrow alleys of the Old City after the 2 p.m. attack, and
large numbers of police searched the area, the report said.
   Dozens of Arabs were rounded up for questioning, Sandori said.
   Cohen was the second Jew killed in Jerusalem since the
Palestinian uprising in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
started December 1987. In June 1988, a Jewish seminary student was
shot and killed by an Arab prostitute, and police said at the time
she had nationalist motives.
   Cohen and his friend, 21-year-old Gavriel Hanukka, were walking
on Mount Zion when they noticed five men who appeared to be Arabs
walking behind them, said Sandori.
   ``Two of the Arabs ran ahead and waited for Cohen and Hanukka in
a little alley way. There, they attacked Cohen, and Hanukka ran to
get help,'' said another police official, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Cohen and Hanukka studied at a Jewish seminary in Maalei Adumim,
a West Bank settlement east of Jerusalem, police said. Cohen was a
Jerusalem resident, police said.
   The last stabbing attack in Jerusalem occurred in May 1988, when
an Arab assailant shouting ``Allahu Akhbar'' (God is great) plunged
a kitchen knife into the back of a 16-year-old Jewish seminary
student. The victim, Chanoch Albeck, suffered a punctured lung but
recovered from the attack.
   Cohen's death brings to 16 the number of Israelis killed during
the uprising against Israeli occupation of the territories they
seized from Arab neighbors in the 1967 Middle East War. More than
380 Palestinians have died.
   The slaying is expected to fuel tension between Arabs and Jews in
this disputed city. Since the start of the uprising, few Jews have
dared enter the Old City and other areas of Israeli-annexed Arab
east Jerusalem.
   The slaying comes about two weeks before Jerusalem's municipal
election, which Arab residents have vowed to boycott in solidarity
with the uprising.
</TEXT>
