<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs     02-18 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Iran-Drugs,0150</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Than 1,700 Addicts Arrested, Radio Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A total of 1,740 drug addicts were
arrested across Iran in a 24-hour sweep that ended Saturday,
state-run Tehran radio reported.
   The radio, monitored in Nicosia, said some of those arrested were
freed after signing declarations ``confessing their regrets.'' It
said the addicts were picked up in Khuzestan, Hamedan, Mazandaran,
Lorestan and western Azarbayejan provinces.
   New drug laws that took effect Jan. 21 impose the death penalty
for anyone possessing small quantities of narcotics. The laws give
addicts a six-month time limit to kick the habit, or face conviction.
   State-run media say there are about 1 million drug addicts in
Iran, which has a population of 50 million, but unofficial estimates
put the figure at 2 million. News reports last week said 175 drug
traffickers have been executed since the new law took effect.
