<FIRST>r i AM-Turkey-Torture     02-18 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turkey-Torture,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Turkey Admits Prison Torture Deaths</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANKARA, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities admitted Saturday that some
prisoners have been tortured to death, but they said the number is
lower than that alleged by Amnesty International.
   In a report published last month, the London-based human rights
group accused Turkish authorities of routinely torturing political
detainees since martial law was imposed in 1980 following a military
takeover.
   Amnesty International said it gave the government a list of 239
men and women alleged to have died from torture and ill-treatment
while in custody.
   A Foreign Ministry statement Saturday said an investigation into
146 of these cases had been completed and showed that torture was
suspected in the deaths of 32 detainees or prisoners in the past
eight years.
   It said that trials in 14 of these cases had resulted in
convictions of 57 people on charges of torture and ill-treatment of
prisoners. Four cases ended in acquittals, and trials in the other
cases are under way, the statement said.
   The ministry said 10 of the people cited as dead by the Amnesty
International were still alive and others had died of natural
causes, suicide, effects of hunger strikes, or in shootouts with
security forces.
   The ministry said all allegations concerning human rights
violations in Turkey were examined ``meticulously.''
   ``But, since most of these allegations are based on insufficient
or incorrect information, it often takes a long time to reach
healthy and satisfactory conclusions,'' it said.
</TEXT>
