<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-US     02-18 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-US,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands March to Support U.S. Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANGELES CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 people, including
barmaids and soldiers, marched to a rally outside a U.S. air base
Saturday to try to drown out a concert sponsored by opponents of
U.S. military bases in the Philippines.
   Authorities reported no violence. But they said the U.S.-run
Clark Air Base closed its main gate while the two groups held rival
events within a few hundred yards of each other at a park nearby.
   The anti-base concert featured dance and vocal performances with
no speeches. City authorities earlier withdrew a permit they gave
the group, but they later reissued it under pressure from members of
the Senate.
   Many senators have criticized the presence of the bases on
Philippine territory and pressed President Corazon Aquino to demand
they be removed.
   Groups for and against the bases have faced off here before.
   Last month, several thousand residents of Angeles City, about 50
miles north of Manila, prevented hundreds of base opponents from
entering the city during a march from Manila. The protesters were
demanding closure of Clark, Subic Bay Naval Base and four other
smaller U.S. facilities in the country.
   Saturday's march through the city and the rally near the base
were organized by the city's Chamber of Commerce. Participants
included local officials led by Mayor Antonio Abad Santos and at
least a dozen government soldiers who marched in civilian clothes.
   Abad Santos said Clark should not be closed because most of the
city's 200,000 residents depend on it for their livelihood.
   ``Even our pickpockets will run out of business if the base is
closed,'' he said.
   Last year, the U.S. and Philippine governments concluded an
agreement allowing the United States to keep the bases until 1991 in
exchange for $962 million in military and economic aid during the
next two years.
   Mrs. Aquino has given no indication of her position on
maintaining the bases beyond 1991.
</TEXT>
