<FIRST>r a AM-HolzerArrested     02-18 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holzer Arrested,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Broadway Producer Adela Holzer Arrested on Larceny Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Broadway producer turned convicted con artist
was held without bail on charges that she stole at least $280,000
from investors by claiming to be the wife of David Rockefeller.
   Adela Holzer, 54, who was a major backer of such hits as ``Hair''
and ``Lenny'' and later served two years in prison for an investment
scam, was arrested Thursday on grand larceny charges and ordered
held without bail at an arraignment Friday.
   ``I believe she was preparing to flee,'' Assistant District
Attorney Christopher Prather said in arguing for the no-bail
provision. ``And I believe she has access to an immense amount of
stolen wealth.''
   Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said Mrs. Holzer
broke free from detectives and tried to run after they grabbed her
outside her apartment building.
   She was arraigned on two counts of second-degree grand larceny
before Criminal Court Judge Bruce Allen. Her lawyer, Robert
Koppelman, said his client would plead innocent.
   Mrs. Holzer is accused of swindling two men, investment counselor
Brian Griffiths and furniture dealer Jack Vallega, out of $280,000.
But Morgenthau said at least 26 investors gave her money and he
suspects she took them for millions of dollars.
   Morgenthau said Mrs. Holzer got the money by falsely telling
investors she was secretly married to Rockefeller, former chairman
of Chase Manhattan Bank, and that he would invest the money and get
a high rate of return in a short period. She accepted a minimum of
$10,000 for investment, promising returns of 48 percent to 82
percent within 90 days, Morgenthau said.
   To support the marriage claim, the district attorney said, Mrs.
Holzer had two certificates, one dating from 1983 and the other from
1987, which purported to show that she and Rockefeller were wed in
Madrid, Spain.
   She also kept a silver-framed photograph of Rockefeller by her
bed, Morgenthau said.
   In fact, the district attorney said, Rockefeller does not know
Mrs. Holzer and has never had any business dealings with her.
Rockefeller, 73, and his wife, Peggy, have been married since 1940.
   Ten years ago, Mrs. Holzer was convicted of swindling investors
in a bogus Toyota dealership in Indonesia and three land scams in
Spain. She served two years of a two-to-six-year sentence.
   If convicted of the latest charges, Mrs. Holzer could face up to
15 years in prison.
   During the 1960s and '70s, she was a major investor in ``Hair,''
``Lenny,'' and ``The Ritz'' and was a producer of several other
Broadway shows. Since she has been out of prison, she reportedly has
been working on three upcoming theatrical projects, including a
planned musical about the late Sen. Joseph McCarthy.
</TEXT>
