<FIRST>u i AM-CentralAmerica Bjt   02-18 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Central America, Bjt,0788</SECOND>
<HEAD>Despite Summit, Means of Contra Disbanding Unresolved</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five Central American presidents
have signed a death warrant for the Contra movement but still must
find a way to carry it out.
   At a summit here last week, the leaders of Costa Rica, El
Salvador, Guatemala, Nicaragua and Honduras committed themselves to
finding a way to disband the U.S.-backed rebel force that has been
fighting Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government for seven years.
   ``It wasn't that the presidents killed the Contras. They merely
affixed a seal to a plain truth _ that the Contras lost the war,''
said a high-ranking diplomat from a nation that will provide troops
for a United Nations monitoring force.
   At the same time, President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua pledged to
move his nation toward democracy.
   Although President Bush was skeptical, others said Ortega has no
alternative as he tries to reconstruct Nicaragua's shattered economy.
   The Central American presidents promised to produce within 90
days a detailed program for the ``demobilization and voluntary
repatriation or relocation'' of the Contras.
   The rebel force consists of about 11,000 fighters and 8,000 to
10,000 family members. The Contras received strong support from the
Reagan administration, but they've been withdrawing from Nicaragua
to border camps in Honduras since Congress cut off military aid in
February 1988.
   Many say they are determined to keep fighting even though it is
extremely unlikely the United States will renew military aid.
   A blueprint for disbanding the Contra force was drafted earlier
this month in meetings at the United Nations in New York. Under the
proposal, Spain, Canada and West Germany would station troops along
the Honduran-Nicaraguan border.
   ``We're talking about small contingents, mostly soldiers, but
unarmed,'' said the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
``One thing these countries don't need is more armies.''
   Foreign ministry officials from the Central American nations will
work with U.N. officials on a final plan, to be approved by the
presidents of their nations.
   The plan might allow some Contras to return to Nicaragua or
settle in Honduras. Others might be relocated to third countries,
including the United States.
   ``Dissolution of the Contras is irreversible,'' the diplomat said.
   He said Honduras ``was fed up to the eyebrows'' with having an
alien armed force on its soil. Moreover, the Contras lost their
patron when Reagan left office, the diplomat said.
   Contra leaders did not agree on the rebels' future in light of
the Central American accord.
   ``If we can't win (militarily), we have to make use of new fields
of action,'' said one leader, Adolfo Calero.
   He said Washington has a moral obligation to the Contra movement
and that it should provide relocation money and visas for rebels who
want to settle in the United States. It would cost between $150
million and $250 million to dismantle the forces, Calero said.
   ``The U.S., whether it likes it or not, is deeply involved in
what's happening,'' he said. ``It has to monitor Sandinista
compliance and support the Central American presidents.''
   Wilfredo Montalvan, like Calero a member of the Contra
directorate, said the rebels will not lay down their arms until the
Sandinistas start carrying out democratic reforms. He did not say
how the Contras could be effective without U.S. aid.
   Enrique Bermudez also said the Contras may continue their fight.
   He was unimpressed with Ortega's pledge to free political
prisoners, hold early elections and allow opposition parties access
to the media.
   ``What Ortega committed himself to was very little,'' said
Bermudez, considered the most hawkish Contra.
   He said Nicaraguan authorities terrorize civilians and that
neighborhood committees keep a Big Brother-like watch over residents.
   President Bush also was leery.
   ``Claims like this have been made at one time only to see those
claims repudiated,'' he said. ``Let's be sure that we not leave the
resistance standing alone, leave them twisting down there without
fulfillment of the methods of democracy on the part of the
Sandinistas.''
   Because the Central American nations reached agreement on the
Contra question, the United States likely will have less flexibility
in how it responds to political changes in Nicaragua.
   The diplomat whose country will participate in the U.N. task
force said Ortega's pledge to bring democracy to his nation was not
so much a concession as a recognition of Nicaragua's state of
affairs.
   ``Nicaragua is in such disastrous economic shape that it has to
reform in order to reconstruct. It has no alternative if it wants
outside support,'' the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
