<FIRST>r i AM-Balloonist     02-18 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Balloonist,0428</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fishermen Rescue Balloonist</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The adventure of a Japanese balloonist who tried to
make the first solo flight across the Pacific ended Saturday night
when fishermen pulled him from a gondola that had been tossed around
in rough seas nearly 12 hours.
   The 38-year-old balloonist, Fumio Niwa, was in good condition
after suffering a severe bout of seasickness, said his spokesman,
Toshiaki Oguri.
   Niwa was picked up close to where he came down Saturday morning,
400 miles off the coast of Minami Torishima, an island 1,550 miles
southeast of Tokyo. He brought the helium-filled balloon down
intentionally.
   After landing in the water, Niwa immediately separated his
gondola from the balloon and bobbed around in the Pacific Ocean
awaiting rescue.
   Oguri said he communicated with Niwa, who spoke by radio on the
59-ton No. 1 Yasuei-Maru. Oguri said he did not know the destination
of the fishing boat. It was towing the gondola, which is six feet in
diameter.
   The balloonist took off Wednesday from his hometown of Yokohama,
near Tokyo, originally planning to reach San Diego _ Yokohama's
sister city _ in about four days by hitching a ride on the
high-altitude jet stream winds that generally blow eastward.
   But the winds were blowing north toward Alaska, forcing Niwa to
stay at a lower altitude, his spokesmen have said.
   Saturday afternoon, Niwa suffered severe sickness from the rough
seas, but he recovered by the time he was rescued, said Kenji
Fukawa, another spokesman for the balloonist.
   Niwa at one point opened a window at the top of his globe-shaped
capsule to get fresh air to combat the seasickness. He also shone a
beam of light into the open sea with a flashlight after dark to help
rescuers spot him, Fukawa said.
   The fishing boat was guided to the site by one of two government
P-3C patrol planes. The other one flew over Niwa's gondola to
monitor his position.
   Attempts to rescue him in a seaplane failed. The government sent
a US-1 seaplane, but it returned with engine problems. A second US-1
proved useless because it arrived after dark.
   The fishing boat initially was delayed by 30-mph winds, which
later diminished.
   Niwa, an experienced balloonist, quit his job with a computer
firm three months ago to prepare for the journey.
   In 1981, four balloonists successfully crossed the Pacific Ocean
by balloon for the first time. No one has traveled the distance
alone.
</TEXT>
