<FIRST>u i PM-WinnieMandela     02-18 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winnie Mandela,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mrs. Mandela Agrees to Remove Bodyguards From Her Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winnie Mandela agreed today to
remove from her home the bodyguards who have been accused of
abducting and beating a black teen-age activist who was later found
dead, a minister said.
   The agreement came soon after the exiled leadership of the
African National Congress said Mrs. Mandela had made mistakes and
had refused to heed earlier requests to disband the youth group,
known as the Mandela United soccer team.
   The Rev. Frank Chikane, who announced the agreement after meeting
with Mrs. Mandela for five hours, told a news conference that she
had asked him to find another place for the youths to stay.
   Chikane, general-secretary of the South African Council of
Churches, said Mrs. Mandela told him she was following instructions
from her husband, Nelson Mandela, the imprisoned leader of the
African National Congress.
   The outlawed ANC is the main guerrilla group fighting to end the
apartheid system of legalized racial discrimination in South Africa.
   The statement from the ANC's exile headquarters in Lusaka,
Zambia, called on anti-arpartheid groups to help her solve the
problem. It was less critical than the condemnation of Mrs. Mandela
that was made Thursday by some of the most prominent leaders of
anti-apartheid organizations inside South Africa.
   Chikane refused to say why Mrs. Mandela had not carried out her
husband's wishes immediately after she visited him in prison on
Wednesday.
   He said he would find another place for the black youths to stay
and make other arrangements for Mrs. Mandela's security. He did not
elaborate.
   She formed the Mandela United soccer club in 1986, saying she
wanted to provide something to do for youths congregating on the
streets near her house.
   But they became a group of bodyguards who lived at the house in
Soweto and were often accused of antagonizing members of the
community.
   Black leaders in Soweto have said they, Mandela and ANC officials
in exile have all called on her to disband the team but she had
refused.
   The controversy came to a head last month when three men told a
community meeting of 150 top anti-apartheid activists the bodyguard
members had abducted them to the Mandela home and beaten them.
   The men said that 14-year-old activist Stompie Seipei was also
taken and beaten but was hurt more seriously and was removed from
them after two days. His body was found dumped in a Soweto field on
Jan. 6 with its throat cut. Police this week identified it in a
morgue and opened a murder investigation.
</TEXT>
