<SECOND>AM-Train Attack,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Eight Killed, 50 Injured in Guerrilla Train Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rightist guerrillas killed eight people
and injured 50 when they attacked a passenger train traveling to
Maputo from Mozambique's border with South Africa, official media
reported Saturday.
   The attack occurred Friday at Movene, 34 miles northwest of
Maputo, the capital, AIM state news agency reported.
   It said rescue teams worked into the night ferrying wounded to
Maputo Central Hospital.
   A hospital spokesman said that of 51 people admitted to the
hospital, one died and 11 were treated and sent home. The other
deaths occurred at the scene of the attack.
   AIM said Movene has been the site of several train attacks, the
last on Feb. 5 when 11 people were killed.
   All the attacks are blamed on guerrillas of the Mozambique
National Resistance, who have been fighting since 1977 to topple the
Marxist government. They were first supported by Rhodesia, then
South Africa, which last year said it has stopped backing the
guerrillas.
