<FIRST>r a AM-PrincipalResigns     02-18 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Principal Resigns,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Principal Resigns After Being Accused Of Making Racist Remarks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white principal accused of making
racist comments about blacks to white students has resigned from his
job and will be reassigned, school officials say.
   Charles Walker is accused of telling white cheerleaders that
associating with blacks would degrade them.
   ``Charlie stepped down this afternoon at Northeast,'' Jerry
Epperson, director of high schools for the East Baton Rouge Parish
school system, said Friday. ``His reason was, basically, he didn't
want to do anything to hurt Northeast High School.''
   Local NAACP chapter President G. Washington Eames said Thursday
he had received a letter written by several black teachers at
Northeast that read:
   ``When a principal summons white cheerleaders to his office and
tells them that their association and friendship with black boys and
girls will cause them to be degraded is the best example of racism
we have ever experienced from a person who calls himself a
professional.''
   Walker has been ``teaching that one race is better than or less
than the other,'' Eames quoted the letter as saying. It said he
``not only frustrated, demoralized and insulted every black child at
this school, but also ... created social degradation and human
humiliation among the black members of this faculty.''
   Walker has an unlisted home phone number and could not be reached
for comment.
   ``Rather than getting involved in some type of turmoil, Charlie
thought it best to step down,'' Epperson said.
   Walker will take one week of annual leave, beginning Monday, and
then will be reassigned to a central office position, Epperson said.
   An interim principal _ who will be from outside Northeast High
and will not be allowed to apply for the permanent position _ will
be named over the weekend, Epperson said.
</TEXT>
