<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan-Libya     02-18 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan-Libya,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>Libyan Minister Proposes New Union</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya's defense minister arrived Saturday
and immediately announced a proposal to form what he called an Arab
Sahel state unifying his country with Oman, North Yemen, South Yemen
and Djibouti.
   Abu-Bakr Younis' proposal came as unity fever seemed to strike
the Arab world.
   On Friday, Libya, Algeria, Tunisia, Mauritania and Morocco set up
a North African ``Union of the Great Arab Maghreb,'' a political and
economic union whose details still are unclear. And on Thursday,
Egypt, Jordan, Iraq and North Yemen formed the Arab Cooperation
Council, an economic organization.
   Younis, whose visit was not announced previously, said he would
discuss strengthening bilateral relations with Sudanese officials.
Last year, Younis ended a visit to Sudan in a huff after Khartoum
rejected a proposed merger of the two countries.
   Younis said he had visited North and South Yemen, Djibouti,
Ethiopia and Somalia.
   He told reporters he was presenting ``a number of unity
projects'' to Arab and African states during his current tour.
   On his Arab Sahel state, he did not explain the relationship of
Oman, North Yemen and South Yemen from the Arabian peninsula,
Djibouti from the Horn of Africa and Libya from North Africa with
the Sahel region of central Africa.
   Younis said the two Yemens responded favorably to his suggestion
of uniting their countries but differences remained that had to be
resolved.
   Younis said Sudan was welcome to join the North African Maghreb
union. Arab officials have said Sudan has expressed interest in
joining the Arab Cooperation Council.
   Younis was holding talks Saturday with Sudan's Prime Minister
Sadek el-Mahdi and Defense Minister Abdul-Magid Khalil.
   He said he would spend two days in the Sudanese capital.
</TEXT>
