<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     02-18 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Warring Cambodians Prepare for Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH L. WHITING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of warring Cambodian factions
and their neighbors meet Sunday for a round of peace talks, but
there was little sign of compromise on a key issue: how to share
power after Vietnam's troops withdraw.
   ``There is still a divergence of views, particularly on some of
the more sensitive internal issues,'' Indonesian Foreign Minister
Ali Alatas told reporters Saturday.
   He was referring to how four factions that have fought for years
can reconcile to rebuild their war-torn country.
   Alatas is chairman of the three-day meeting involving Vietnam,
the administration it set up in Phnom Penh early in 1979 and three
guerrilla resistance groups.
   Also taking part are Laos and the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations, comprising the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Malaysia,
Indonesia and Brunei.
   Alatas held three days of preparatory talks with Cambodian
leaders.
   ``The possibility of reaching further common ground is quite real
... Although we did not agree on all the issues, at least this was
the first time we ranged over all the major elements of a possible
solution,'' he told reporters. These included a Vietnamese pullout,
halting military aid to the resistance, and a peacekeeping or other
force to maintain stability during the transition.
   The next step could be a formal international conference, said
Alatas.
   On arriving Saturday in Jakarta, Vietnamese Foreign Minister
Nguyen Co Thach said 50 percent of the problem has been solved.
   And Prime Minister Hun Sen of the Phnom Penh government added,
``I believe we have come to the final stage of the problem.''
   Khieu Samphan, nominal leader of the largest guerrilla group, the
communist Khmer Rouge, said in a statement he would spare no efforts
to find a solution, but he restated a peace plan already rejected by
his foes.
   The rest of the sometimes shaky guerrilla alliance includes
anti-communists under deposed Prime Minister Son Sann and Prince
Norodom Sihanouk.
   Sihanouk heads the coalition but has refused to come to Jakarta
because his personal peace plan has been rejected. His son will
represent his faction.
   The Khmer Rouge is considered by far the most potent of the rebel
forces. Its government was ousted by invading Vietnamese troops
after it caused the deaths of hundreds of thousands in trying to
create an agrarian communist society.
   Foreign ministers of Cambodia, Laos and Vietnam issued a joint
statement in Phnom Penh on Friday saying the withdrawal of
Vietnamese troops from Cambodia no longer is a major issue. The
outstanding problem, they said, is to prevent the Khmer Rouge
returning to power.
</TEXT>
