   First City's predecessor sued Connally several years ago to
collect on a bad debt, but the dispute has since been settled, Day
said.
   Since leaving the law firm of Vinson &amp; Elkins, where he was a
partner for many years, Connally has quietly run a small consulting
firm and last year made a cameo appearance in print and television
ads for University Savings Association.
   Connally was governor of Texas from 1963 to 1969, and was wounded
in the assassination of President Kennedy in 1963 in Dallas. He was
a presidential candidate in 1968, 1976 and 1980.
   Connally filed for personal and business bankruptcy in August
1987, listing more than $170 million in debts. His financial
problems prompted First City National Bank, then part of old First
City Bancorp., to sue him for $3 million in connection with an
unpaid loan.
