<FIRST>r a AM-SeaLions     02-18 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sea Lions,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Sea Lion Dies in Transfer Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second captured California sea lion has died and
officials said Saturday they will no longer use drugs to anesthesize
the 600-pound animals before moving them to the southwestern
Washington coast.
   So far, four sea lions have been captured as part of an effort to
keep them from eating steelhead trout migrating from Puget Sound to
Lake Washington through a ship canal. Two of the four have died, the
latest one Friday night.
   Both died as they were coming out of an anesthetic, said Hal
Alabaster, spokesman for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration.
   The second animal to survive the capture and drugging was to be
trucked to the Washington coast for release along the Long Beach
Peninsula. The first sea lion was released there Thursday.
   The second sea lion to die had seemed to be recovering when it
collapsed late Friday night, Alabaster said. ``It appeared to be the
most robust and the strongest of them all,'' he said.
   An autopsy was planned.
   After the first sea lion died, officials said the effects of the
anesthetic may have been aggravated by a severe lung infection and a
bullet wound found on it. The drug used was Telazol, a muscle
relaxant.
   Alabaster said wildlife officials involved in the program plan to
continue capturing the animals, which are protected by federal law,
in a buoy-mounted cage and will try to find a way of fitting them
with radio transmitters and moving them without using drugs.
   ``We've lost two animals. We need to re-evaluate it,'' he said.
``The program wasn't designed to kill animals.''
   He said there is not a lot of experience in working with drugged
sea lions, but that drugs were used because a ``600-pound wild
animal is a dangerous thing to try to handle without being under
sedation.''
   The practice of using drugs had been criticized by environmental
activists, who said it was not necessary to put the animals under to
remove them.
   The sea lions are being moved because they are eating the run of
steelhead trout that goes through the Ballard Locks to enter Lake
Washington on their way to spawning grounds.
</TEXT>
