<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Rushdie-Censorship     02-18 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushdie-Censorship,0507</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie Has History Of Past Censorship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS K. GERANIOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie, author of ``The Satanic Verses,'' had faced
censorship before his latest novel caused an uproar in the Islamic
world and led to threats against his life.
   He had two run-ins with censors in Pakistan, according to an
essay Rushdie contributed to an anthology on censorship with the
ironic title ``They Shoot Writers, Don't They?'' published by Faber
and Faber Ltd., of London, in 1984.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' has drawn calls from the Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini for the author's execution. Several countries have
banned the novel and a number of U.S. book stores, including the B.
Dalton and Waldenbooks chains, have pulled it from their shelves.
   Moslems contend the novel blasphemes the prophet Mohammed.
   Rushdie's essay, titled ``Casualties of Censorship,'' was written
for the magazine ``Index on Censorship'' in 1983.
   ``My first direct contact with censorship took place in 1968,
when I was twenty-one, fresh out of Cambridge and full of the
radical fervour of that famous year,'' Rushdie wrote.
   Commissioned by a magazine to write his impressions of returning
home to Pakistan, Rushdie said he remembered little about the piece
except ``images of dying horses with flies settling on their
eyeballs.''
   Several weeks later he learned from the magazine editor that
official government censors had banned the article.
   Quizzing an uncle who served on the censorship panel, Rushie
quoted him as saying: ``Publication would not be in your best
interests.''
   ``I never found out why,'' the author said.
   On another occasion, Rushdie persuaded Karachi TV to let him
produce Edward Albee's ``The Zoo Story.''
   ``I then had to go through a series of astonishing censorship
conferences,'' he wrote.
   He was ordered to remove references in the play to pork, which
Moslems aren't allowed to eat, sex and homosexuality, he wrote.
   Rushdie stood his ground on pork, even though he was told the
word could not be spoken on Pakistani television.
   ``Pork, in Albee's view, made hamburgers so disgusting that even
dogs refused them,'' Rushdie wrote. ``This was superb anti-pork
propaganda.''
   But the television executives were unswayed and made even more
demands, Rushdie wrote.
   ``I also had to cut the line about God being a coloured queen who
wears a kimono and plucks his eyebrows,'' he wrote.
   ``The point I'm making is not that censorship is a source of
amusement, which it usually isn't, but that _ in Pakistan, at any
rate _ it is everywhere, inescapable, permitting no appeal,'' he
wrote.
   ``What are the effects of total censorship? Obviously, the
absence of information and the presence of lies,'' he wrote.
   ``But the worst, most insidious effect of censorship is that, in
the end, it can deaden the imagination of the people,'' he wrote.
``It becomes easy to think that what has been suppressed was
valueless anyway, or so dangerous that it needed to be suppressed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890218-0042 </DOCNO>
