<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--WoodenBridge     02-18 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Wooden Bridge,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wood To Be Used To Replace Rusting Steel Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWICH, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 38-foot bridge closed because officials
feared it could collapse will have its rusting steel girders
replaced by wood as part of Vermont's new bridge modernization
program.
   The Meadow Brook Bridge, which has a wooden deck and rails, was
closed last summer by selectmen who worried that its rusting steel
support girders would no longer stand up to truck traffic.
   Wooden bridges save money in the short and the long run because
they are cheaper to build, don't have to be painted and are immune
to salt, said Dennis Borchardt of the George D. Aiken Resource
Conservation and Development Area, a non-profit organization
dedicated to helping find better uses for local resources.
   The project should be completed in June.
</TEXT>
