<FIRST>d w AMUS-Japan     02-18 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM=US-Japan,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Long-Term Means of Easing U.S.-Japanese Tension Urged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-Japanese commission should be
established to anticipate and solve disputes before they boil over,
says a prominent U.S. specialist on East Asian affairs.
   Robert Scalapino told a news briefing Friday he hopes President
Bush will propose to the Japanese such a joint commission to take up
problems in advance instead of allowing them ``to reach political
white heat level.''
   The two countries ``stand at a crossroads in our relations'' and
must move toward resolution of conflicts through negotiations and
compromise, said Scalapino, who heads the East Asian institute at
the University of California in Berkeley.
   Bush leaves Wednesday for Japan, China and South Korea. There may
be too little time for such matters during the planned one-day stop
in Tokyo for Emperor Hirohito's funeral but they need to be taken up
soon, Scalapino said.
   ``I think it is quite clear that if we are asking Japan to play a
larger and more responsible role in the world, we also have to share
some of the decision-making process with Japan,'' said Scalapino.
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita in a recent visit to Washington
called for closer U.S.-Japanese consultation on regional and global
issues.
   In the complex U.S.-Japanese relationship, prospects are ``that
acrimony will not end, that this will continue to be a troubled
marriage,'' Scalapino said.
   U.S.-Japanese relations are smoother in security matters than
trade, but the United States has not made clear what is ultimately
expected of Japan, Scalapino said.
   Scalpino took issue with the view that it is inevitable for an
economic power such as Japan to become a military power.
   ``Apart from the fact that the Japanese people do not want a high
posture military position, and the rest of Asia does not want this,
it is also clear that the Asia of the 1980s and 1990s is not the
Asia of the 1930s,'' he said.
   ``There's no power vacuum on the continent of Asia. There's no
Japanese empire to defend, there are no Western colonial enclaves to
liberate.''
   ``A great fluidity in major power relations'' exists, Scalapino
said, because each of the major players ``with the possible
exception of Japan, has serious domestic problems, and they want a
lower cost, lower risk foreign policy.''
   Hugh T. Patrick of Columbia University forecast that Japan's
trade surpluses with the United States and the world would persist.
   ``At the same time, Japan has a lot of problems _ the runup in
stock prices and land prices poses the specter of a crash in those
markets,'' said Patrick, who heads the Japanese Economy center at
Columbia's graduate business school.
   A key issue in any Bush-Takeshita talk, he said, would be
cooperation in the current round of global trade negotiations while
simultaneously enabling Japan ``from the Japanese perspective to
protect its agriculture and from the American perspective to open
its agriculture.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
