<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-89 1552EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Rushdie 1stLd-Writethru   02-18 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Rushdie, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0554,0503</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Iran's Official News Agency Rejects Rushdie Apology</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Retransmitting a0558 to restore writethru designation.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's official news agency said Saturday
that Salman Rushdie's apology to Moslems for his novel ``The Satanic
Verses'' was insufficient because he didn't repent and order the
book withdrawn.
   A later report from the Islamic Republic News Agency indicated
the apology was accepted, but a dispatch later asked editors to note
that it was ``in fact the personal observation of the copy writer
and that it does not allow for any specific interpretation
whatsoever.''
   The government-run agency's initial reaction to Rushdie's
statement said it fell short of the apology demanded by President
Ali Khamenei to void a death sentence imposed on Rushdie by
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
   Later, IRNA said that Rushdie's apology, ``though far too short
of a repentance, is generally seen as sufficient enough to warrant
his pardon by the masses in Iran and elsewhere in the world.''
   The disclaimer came two hours later.
   IRNA also reported that the Persian daily Ettela'at wrote that
``to pay one man to kill another man is murder at a premium and not
a religiously-inspired act.''
   Khomeini, Iran's leader, on Tuesday issued a ``fatwa,'' or
religious ruling, saying that Rushdie should be killed because of
his novel, ``The Satanic Verses,'' which some say insults Islam.
   The reported newspaper commentary amounted to an unusual
challenge to actions by Iran's religious leaders, who took
Khomeini's ruling as a cue to offer a total of $5.2 million to
whomever kills Rushdie.
   Rushdie's book has been banned in six countries, including Iran,
and removed from the shelves of major bookstores in the United
States. It has prompted protests in Iran, India, and other countries.
   Rushdie and his wife have been in hiding, reportedly protected by
armed guards, since Khomeini ordered his death.
   Iran's president said Friday that Rushdie, an Indian-born Briton
from a Moslem family, might be able to save his life by admitting he
blundered.
   IRNA quoted the newspaper as saying the price put on Rushdie's
life was ``typical of the dealings of the underworld _ and not of
the saints or religious men.''
   The newspaper said that the government-run 15th-of-Khordad
Foundation and other sponsors jumping in to up the bounty ``had
increased the bounty to a staggering figure completely overshadowing
its religious implications,'' IRNA said.
   The newspaper was quoted as saying any person trying to kill the
writer will be prompted by greed _ not religious principles.
   At a Cabinet meeting earlier Saturday, the ministers had urged
religious leaders to keep alert to any plots against Islam from the
West similar to Rushdie's book, IRNA reported.
   The London-based Islamic Society for the Promotion of Religious
Tolerance said in a statement: ``We very much welcome Mr. Rushdie's
apology and hope that it will now pave the way out of this
unfortunate crisis.''
</TEXT>
