<FIRST>r i AM-Haiti     02-18 0303</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avril Reshuffles Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Lt. Gen. Prosper Avril has
reshuffled his Cabinet for the first time since he seized power in a
coup last year, an independent report said Saturday.
   The government named Col. Acedius Saint-Louis as the new defense
and interior minister and Augustin Romain Ceme as new justice
minister, according to radio Haiti-Inter.
   Saint-Louis was information minister under Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy,
who was ousted in the September coup. Saint-Louis had been denounced
as repressive by the presidential guardsmen who toppled the Namphy
dictatorship, and he was removed from his office at army
headquarters after the coup.
   Gilbert Austin, former minister of justice, was named president
of the Supreme Court of Appeals, the radio report said.
   The well-known opposition leader Daniel Narcisse was named
assistant commissioner of the newly-created Commission for Haitians
Abroad.
   But the most unpopular of Avril's ministers, including
Information Minister Anthony Virginie Saint-Pierre, remained in
office.
   Since the leak of an Information Ministry memorandum in January,
Saint-Pierre has been widely criticized.
   In his memorandum, Saint-Pierre said a peasant uprising, fomented
by popular organizations, was imminent and ``might have to be put
down with bloodshed.'' He recommended preventive measures.
   An opposition leader said Avril's shakeup should have gone
further.
   ``These are not the reforms we were asking for. We will keep on
asking until we get them,'' Serge Gilles, leader of the National
Progressive Revolutionary Party said.
   Last week, he demanded the ouster of what he views as
anti-democratic elements in the Cabinet, which has remained intact
since Avril was swept into power by a military coup on Sept. 17,
1988.
   Popular support for his government, which pledged to restore
democracy, has plummeted in the past month during a wave of
anti-government demonstrations and two general strikes.
</TEXT>
