<FIRST>r a AM-US-Rushdie     02-18 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Rushdie,0786</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buyers' Frenzy Erupts Over `Satanic Verses'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Satanic Verses, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The decision by large bookstore chains to stop displaying or
selling ``The Satanic Verses'' triggered a buyers' frenzy and
shortages at independent stores, dealers said Saturday.
   ``We got in 25 copies yesterday; they were all reserved,'' said
John Evans, owner of Lemuria Bookstores in Jackson, Miss. ``I wish I
had been smart enough to order 150 _ I blew it.''
   ``I think the right honorable Khomeini is making a best seller
out of it,'' said Sam Weller, owner of the Zion Book Stores in Salt
Lake City, where neither the stores nor the public library could
keep the popular $19.95 novel on their shelves.
   ``Nobody bought it until they started hollering about it,''
agreed Howard Canada, owner of Howard's Bookstore in Bloomington,
Ind.
   The independents said their sales heated up after the Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini offered a bounty Tuesday for the killing of ``The
Satanic Verses'' author Salman Rushdie and his publishers.
   On Friday, the B. Dalton and Barnes &amp; Noble chains, which have
more than 1,250 stores, said they would pull the book from their
shelves, but a spokesman refused to say whether it would not be sold
at all or simply not displayed. Waldenbooks, the nation's largest
bookseller, directed its stores Thursday to remove the book from
shelves, but to sell it upon request.
   Rushdie apologized on Saturday, saying he regretted if the book
distressed ``sincere followers of Islam,'' but it was not clear
whether Iran would accept his remarks.
   Rebecca Morehouse, manager of a Waldenbooks store in San
Francisco, said the company's president told stores Saturday that
they may display the book if they don't feel threatened.
   She wanted to sell the book, but ``I'm just not going to wave it
like a red flag in front of a bull.'' Her store was out of stock and
awaiting a second printing.
   The small stores also couldn't get enough.
   ``Some of my customers called and wanted to buy it; they didn't
want to read it _ they just wanted to make a political statement,''
said Dave Unowsky, owner of the sold-out Hungry Mind bookstore in
St. Paul, Minn., and a board member of the American Booksellers
Association.
   ``We've gotten hundreds of the requests in the past hundreds of
days,'' said an employee, who identified himself only as Pat, at New
York City's Coliseum bookstore. He said the store had sold 155
copies since the end of December, with the ``big sales'' starting
two weeks ago.
   ``When the book was first published, we got 50 or 60 copies and
sold them immediately; yesterday, by 1 o'clock, we had over 50 phone
requests,'' said Fred Bass, owner of the Strand bookstore in New
York City.
   ``There's been tremendous demand since Wednesday and there's no
way I can get more. I've already had a call from somebody who
offered me $40 for a copy,'' said Bass.
   ``I think you'll start seeing first editions on the market very
quickly. $50 to $75,'' said Evans. ``I'm talking about 30 days, 60
days.''
   Even if the apology is accepted, ``I think it will still be
popular,'' Bass said.
   Readers who want to judge ``The Satanic Verses'' for themselves
also have been snapping up the Koran, said Bass. The Strand, which
normally sells about 10 copies of the Koran a week, has sold about
200 in the last 10 days.
   Meanwhile, authors Norman Mailer, Gay Talese, E.L. Doctorow,
Susan Sontag and Robert Stone planned a public reading Wednesday in
New York City of selections from ``The Satanic Verses'' and other
Rushdie writings.
   Unlike the big chains, small bookstores expressed little fear of
retribution for selling ``The Satanic Verses.''
   ``I did instruct the staff to take it out of the window on
Thursday ... for fear of a brick being thrown,'' said Philip Lyman,
manager of the Gotham bookstore in New York City, which has sold out.
   ``We've had no threats, but Viking had called us and told us not
to display it in our window,'' said the Coliseum employee.
   ``We've had some complaints, with people threatening to boycott
the store,'' but no threats of violence, said Matt Miller, manager
of the Tattered Cover in Denver.
   ``There is a question of safety, obviously, especially on the
East Coast,'' said Kevin Morrisey, an employee at the St. Paul
bookstore. ``But we haven't had any threats. If there are any
fundamentalist Muslims in this area, I'm not aware of them.''
   ``Nah,'' said Evans when asked if he feared Moslem retribution.
``In Mississippi?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
