<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary     02-18 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungary's Writers Protest Havel Trial; Romanian Refugees Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official Hungarian Writers' Union
has protested the jailing of Czech playwright and activist Vaclav
Havel, Hungary's official news agency said Saturday.
   MTI said the Writers' Union expressed its ``anxiety'' in a letter
to Czech Ambassador Vlastimil Ehrenberger.
   Havel goes on trial in Prague on Tuesday on charges of incitement
and obstructing the duty of a public official. He could face up to
2{ years in jail if convicted.
   Havel was arrested Jan. 16 after he and eight other dissidents,
to be tried in another Prague court on Tuesday, laid flowers in
memory of Jan Palach, a student who burned himself to death to
protest the Soviet-led invasion that ended the so-called Prague
Spring reforms of 1968.
   It was believed to be the first time an official Writers' Union
has written an allied government of the Warsaw Pact protesting
treatment of a dissident.
   The United States and Britain on Friday called for Havel's
release and the release of the eight other activists.
   Also Saturday, a dozen ethnic Hungarians from Romania who took
refuge in the Hungarian Embassy in Sofia, Bulgaria, in September
arrived in Hungary after Bulgaria agreed to let them emigrate, MTI
said.
   The 12 defected while on a tourist trip to Bulgaria last year and
sought refuge at the Hungarian Embassy on Sept. 14, where they
remained until Friday.
   In a report from Sofia, MTI said Bulgarian authorities accepted a
proposal by the Geneva-based International Red Cross ``for
humanitarian considerations.''
   The involvement of three Soviet bloc countries in a political
refugee case was unprecedented and came at a time when
Hungarian-Romanian relations have been severely strained over
Romania's alleged discrimination against 1.7 million ethnic
Hungarians.
   In another development, families of Hungary's leaders executed
after the 1956 anti-communist revolt have decided to rebury the
leaders in marked graves on June 16, the anniversary of their
execution in 1958, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   Last month, the Hungarian government agreed to allow the
exhumation from unmarked graves and the reburial of the country's
leader during the uprising, Imre Nagy, and his associates.
   The government daily Magyar Hirlap Saturday quoted Janos Veszi,
Nagy's son-in-law, as saying the reburial date has formally been
submitted to the Ministry of Justice.
   The ruling Communist party at a Central Committee meeting last
week partially reassessed the 1956 revolt after Imre Pozsgay, a
leading reformer in the leadership, said it was a popular uprising
rather than a counter-revolution as it had been officially termed
for 32 years.
   The communist leadership reached a compromise formulation on the
events, saying they featured both popular and counterrevolutionary
elements.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
