<DOCNO> AP890218-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-89 1749EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Exports     02-18 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Exports,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Companies Delivered Equipment For Pakistan Nuke Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German companies have delivered
equipment to Pakistan for years that can be used to make nuclear
weapons, a magazine reported Saturday.
   Der Spiegel said West German companies delivered machinery and
technology to Pakistan that was ``adapted'' to the nation's nuclear
energy and weapons development program.
   The Hamburg-based magazine, in a telex to other news media
Saturday, said the equipment ranged from tooling equipment to
technology capable of processing tritium gas, used to enhance
nuclear weapons.
   Der Spiegel said many of the exports were made with government
approval though the magazine said U.S. officials contended the
machinery could be used to make parts for nuclear warheads.
   Der Spiegel said customs officials only learned later that the
machinery was used in nuclear research and development.
   The magazine said the Nuclear Reasearch Center in Karlsruhe, of
which the government owns a controlling interest, also delivered
equipment to Pakistan and trained Pakistani researchers.
   In its telex, Der Spiegel did not name the companies allegedly
involved in the exports.
   The magazine said U.S. officials asked West German officials for
years to help prevent Pakistan from developing nuclear weapons.
Pakistan has said its nuclear research has only been for energy
purposes.
   West German companies have also been linked to development of a
suspected poison gas factory in Libya.
   The government has said it plans to implement tough new export
rules to prevent the export of equipment and materials that could be
used to make chemical or nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
