<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-18 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ice And Heavy Snow Over virginia And Carolinas, Washington</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow fell Saturday over the central Atlantic Coast and the
Northwest, while light snow fell over the northern Plains.
   A low-pressure system off the coast of North Carolina circulated
moisture from the Atlantic back over Virginia and the Carolinas,
producing ice and heavy snow.
   Winter storm warnings were posted for upstate South Carolina,
western and northern North Carolina, and south-central and eastern
Virginia.
   By midday, Norfolk, Va., had 11.2 inches of snow, the second
highest total on record there for February. Up to 14 inches of snow
had fallen at Williamsburg, Va., and in northern North Carolina's
Warren and Stokes counties.
   Sleet and freezing rain coated other parts of Virginia and the
Carolinas, and ice accumulating on branches and power lines caused
scattered power outages in the Carolinas.
   In the Northwest, steady snow fell Saturday on the eastern
two-thirds of Washington state as the most severe snowstorm to hit
the state this winter slowed traffic to a crawl, especially in
mountain passes. Spokane, Wash., had 13 inches of new snow.
   A winter storm warning was posted throughout the night for the
central mountains and northern panhandle of Idaho, where up to 8
inches of snow was possible.
   Light snow fell was over parts of Minnesota, South Dakota,
Nebraska, Iowa, Illinois and Wisconsin.
   Rain fell over the northern and central Pacific Coast region, and
over the central Gulf Coast states.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees below zero at Glasgow and Havre, Mont., to 84 at Fort Myers,
Fla. Saturday morning's low for the Lower 48 states was 33 degrees
below zero at Hibbing, Minn.
   For Sunday, snow was forecast from the western Rockies to the
middle Mississippi Valley. Scattered snow showers were forecast over
the Northeast. Rain was forecast over the northern Pacific Coast,
with scattered showers across the central Pacific Coast. Widely
scattered showers were forecast over south-central Texas and the
Southeast.
   Highs remaining below freezing were predicted from eastern
Washington state through Nebraska and the Dakotas to New England,
with highs only in the teens from northern Montana to northern
Minnesota, and over northern Maine; above 50 from the coast of
California through the southern Plains to the southern Atlantic
Coast; in the 70s in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and lower
80s across the Florida Peninsula.
</TEXT>
