<FIRST>r a AM-BertolottiExecution     02-18 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bertolotti Execution,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Execution Scheduled For Convicted Sex-Slayer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACKIE HALLIFAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man facing execution won his fourth
stay in a week Saturday, just seven hours before he was scheduled to
die for the 1983 sex-slaying of an Orlando woman, court and state
officials said.
   Anthony Bertolotti's execution, which had been set for 7:01 p.m.
Saturday, was immediately rescheduled after Paul Roney, chief judge
of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta, extended a
stay a three-judge panel had issued Friday afternoon.
   The state reset the execution for 7:01 a.m. Tuesday, one minute
after the 60-hour extension expires, according to Jon Peck, a
spokesman for Gov. Bob Martinez.
   Bertolotti was originally set to die last Wednesday morning, but
he won a 24-hour stay from a federal judge in Orlando and then an
additional 24-hour stay from the 11th Circuit. After each stay, the
state rescheduled the execution.
   The latest death warrant, Bertolotti's second, is effective until
Wednesday morning. Bertolotti survived his first death warrant when
the state Supreme Court stayed his exectution in late 1987.
   Florida has executed 20 men since the state resumed capital
punishment in 1979.
   On Jan. 24, Florida executed Ted Bundy for the 1978 slaying of a
12-year-old Lake City girl. In the days before his death, Bundy
confessed to about two dozen slayings of young women in the western
United States.
   Saturday's extension was granted so the full appeals court could
be polled at the request of the Florida Office of the Capital
Collateral Representative, the state agency which represents most
indigent death-row inmates. The state agency's motion asked that the
full court reconsider Friday's decision by the three-judge panel to
deny Bertolotti's appeal.
   Bertolotti, 36, was sentenced in 1984 to die in the electric
chair at Florida State Prison near Starke for the stabbing death of
Carol Ward, 46.
   Bob Macmaster, a spokesman for the state Department of
Corrections, said Bertolotti met with three attorneys Saturday
morning.
   The governor had been in Atlanta en route to Europe for a trade
mission, but after the stay was issued he put his trip off until
Tuesday and returned to Tallahassee, Peck said. Martinez could give
the execution order by telephone from Atlanta or Europe, but thought
it more appropriate that he be in Tallahassee, Peck said.
   According to trial evidence, which included two recorded
confessions, Bertolotti was walking through an Orlando neighborhood
on Sept. 27, 1983, when he saw Ms. Ward carrying groceries into her
home.
   Bertolotti said he persuaded her to let him into the house by
asking to use the telephone. He grabbed a knife, robbed her of $30,
raped her and stabbed her 14 times in the chest and stomach.
   Bertolotti wrote several letters to prosecutors after his
conviction saying ``I have no regrets or sorrows for the murder of
Carol Ward.''
   Appeal attorneys contended Bertolotti's trial lawyers were
negligent because they did not have an expert determine his sanity
before trial.
   The slaying occurred less than a year after Bertolotti's release
from prison, where he served three years of a seven-year term for
aggravated assault.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
