<FIRST>r a AM-PrisonFire     02-18 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison Fire,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prison Fire Destroys Dining Hall</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BI1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fire gutted the state penitentiary's main
dining hall, and officials served prisoners in their cells Saturday,
authorities said.
   One correctional officer and one inmate were treated for smoke
inhalation, but no one was seriously injured in Friday night's fire,
said prison Warden Tom Powers.
   The fire also damaged some fencing and ``we do have some security
concerns,'' Powers said. ``We'll take whatever temporary security
precautions we need.''
   He said officials assume the cause of the fire was electrical.
   No prisoners were in the building when the blaze broke out,
Powers said. The three-story building housed a chapel, recreation
room and the prison's main kitchen and dining area, but had no
cells, the warden said.
   Powers said 185 of the 450 inmates were moved from their cells in
another building to avoid smoke, and 30 to 35 inmates were not able
to immediately return to their cells Saturday. There were no reports
of discipline problems.
   ``The inmates here have been very mature,'' he said.
   National Guard units helped set up a tent kitchen, which will
serve as the meal preparation area until a permanent structure can
be built, Powers said.
   Damage estimates were not immediately available, but prison
officials said earlier plans to raze and replace the 79-year-old
building had estimated the project's cost at $6.07 million.
</TEXT>
