<FILEID>AP-NR-02-18-89 1914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghan-King 1stLd-Writethru a0527 02-18 0841</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-King, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0527,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Afghans Want Return of King to Ensure Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS 13th pvs, ``Najib, the..., with 1 graf to UPDATE with
king's denying he's receieved emissaries from Kabul. Pick up 14th pvs,
``Support for...'' ^By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moderate Afghan groups are pushing for
the restoration of Afghanistan's last king as the only way to avoid
a bloody struggle between rival guerrilla groups.
   But powerful fundamentalist parties among Moslem guerrillas
fighting the Afghan government say they will never allow the return
of the monarchy.
   King Zahir Shah, who was deposed in 1973, is the only Afghan
leader who enjoys broad support that cuts across party, tribal and
ethnic lines, according to some Afghan exiles and analysts.
   The 74-year-old king, who lives in exile in Rome, is the one
figure who may be able to unite a majority of Afghans in the deeply
divided nation, they say.
   ``People think the king is the only person who can command the
support of the entire nation and form the broadest possible
government,'' said Akbar Nakiyar, an official of the moderate Afghan
National Liberation Front.
   Calls for the king's return have gained urgency since the Soviets
ended their nine-year intervention in Afghanistan last week by
pulling out the last of their troops.
   Guerrilla commanders say the weak Afghan communist government
cannot survive long, and they are preparing to take over.
   Zahir Shah has strong support among many Afghans who remember his
liberal rule as benign and progressive, analysts said. The king is
also deeply respected as a modest man, they said.
   A 1988 study by the Afghan Information Center indicated up to 70
percent of Afghans would support the return of Zahir Shah.
   Crowds of up to 50,000 Afghan refugees have taken part in
demonstrations in Pakistan in recent months to support the return of
the monarch, guerrilla officials say. Hard-line guerrillas with
clubs broke up one such demonstration in early February in Peshawar.
   Zahir Shah, who has lived for years in seclusion at a villa in
Rome, said recently that he was willing to return to help rebuild
Afghanistan.
   ``Now that the Afghan nation is about to achieve the aims of its
heroic struggle, I wish to reiterate yet again that I am prepared to
render, without any claim or precondition, any service to my country
which would reflect the will of the majority of my compatriots,'' he
said.
   Najib, the president of the Soviet-supported government in Kabul,
said Friday he had sent emissaries to Rome to sound out the king. A
spokesman for the king, General Abdul Wali, denied that Saturday,
saying: ``We have not received anyone from Kabul ... and we don't
expect to receive anyone soon.''
   Support for the king has increased as the seven main guerrilla
parties, long bitter rivals, have feuded over power and territory,
analysts say. Critics charge some guerrilla leaders are intent on
grabbing power rather than safeguarding the interests of the Afghan
people.
   ``Afghans want a leader who will represent the nation's interests
and not be selfishly fighting for power,'' said Naim Majrooh, head
of the Afghan Information Center. ``There is no other focal point
that everybody can agree on.''
   Afghanistan could be plunged into new conflict if the rival
guerrilla groups oust the communist government and then compete for
power.
   ``There would be a civil war if the political parties impose a
government on the Afghan people. The Russians found that out,'' said
Homayoun Assef, a cousin of Zahir Shah.
   The king would have to mount a drive for support if he wants to
return to Afghanistan, analysts said. Whether he is willing to do so
is not clear, they said.
   Of the seven main parties that make up the guerrilla alliance,
four are considered hard-line groups and they strongly oppose the
king. The three moderate factions say his return is a possibility
that must be considered.
   Hardliners say royalty is no longer a viable means of government.
   ``The king is a part of Afghan history. You can't go back. Zahir
Shah is part of the past,'' said Abdul Hadi Arghandehwal, of the
Hezbi-i-Islmai faction.
   Fundamentalists charge the king was under communist control
because he supported modern, secular reforms in the poor and
backward central Asian nation.
   Hard-line parties trace their roots to fundamentalist groups that
opposed the king and then his nephew, Mohammad Daoud, who seized
power in a 1973 palace coup. Daoud, who declared a republic, was
toppled and killed when communists seized power in a 1978 coup.
   Some members of the moderate guerrilla parties openly support the
return of Zahir Shah. Others say the monarchy should not be restored
but that Zahir Shah should come back as the acting head of state.
   Other guerrilla officials say support for Zahir Shah is based on
nostalgia for the peaceful days before the civil war began in 1978.
The country has changed enormously since then and the traditional
society on which royalist rule was based has disappeared forever,
they said.
</TEXT>
