<FIRST>r a AM-SakharovVisit     02-18 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov Visit,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sakharovs Visit Family in Boston</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet physicist Andrei Sakharov and his wife,
Yelena Bonner, arrived in Boston Saturday for their first visit
together with relatives.
   The Sakharovs declined comment at Logan International Airport,
with Bonner saying the couple wanted ``private time.''
   The couple had been in Canada for a week where Sakharov received
a humanitarian award Friday night from the St. Boniface Hospital
Research Foundation. Sakharov received the $20,000 award in
Winnipeg, Canada.
   The Boston visit was to give Sakharov and his wife a chance to
see their grandchildren in suburban Newton before returning to
Moscow, said Efrem Yankelevich, who is married to Bonner's daughter,
Tatiana.
   ``As far as I know he does not intend to make any public
appearances. He will be here I don't know how long but probably just
for a few days and then he goes back to Moscow,'' Yankelevich said.
   Two of Bonner's children live in Boston suburbs.
   Sakharov, who won the 1975 Nobel Peace Prize for his human rights
activities, left the Soviet Union earlier this month, visiting Italy
before going to Canada.
   He visited the United States for four weeks last fall, his first
visit to the West. He came as a Soviet delegate to the International
Foundation for the Survival and Development of Humanity, an
organization formed last year by Soviet and American scientists to
foster cooperation on arms control, hunger, pollution and other
issues.
   Bonner did not accompany her husband last fall but has made
previous visits alone to the United States.
   Sakharov, who helped develop the Soviet hydrogen bomb, previously
was barred from traveling abroad because of his past scientific work.
</TEXT>
