<FIRST>r w AM-AFL-CIOMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0503 02-18 0764</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AFL-CIO Meeting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0503,750</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Leaders Hoping for Fresh Start with Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; SUBS penultimate graf to correct spelling of `Donahue'; picks
up last graf pvs, bgng: ``I do...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFL-CIO leaders hold their annual meeting this
week united in hoping for improved relations with the White House
but divided over what labor must do to improve its standing in the
workplace.
   The weeklong gathering in Bal Harbour, Fla., will feature the
first meeting between the federation's Executive Council and new
Labor Secretary Elizabeth Dole. Union officials are looking to begin
on a better note with the Bush administration after turbulent
relations in the Reagan era.
   ``Mine will be a message of cooperation,'' Mrs. Dole said last
week. She said she would encourage improved labor-management
relations and promise to listen to the concerns of unions.
   That would be an improvement over the first meeting between the
35-member Executive Council and Reagan's first labor secretary,
Raymond Donovan.
   The labor leaders and Donovan clashed over Reagan's economic
plans after their first meeting. Six months later Reagan fired
striking air traffic controllers, effectively killing their union
and permanently damaging the administration's standing with labor.
   AFL-CIO President Lane Kirkland has been cautious in assessing
the prospects for warmed up relations between the federation and the
White House.
   ``I hope so, more I can't say,'' he said recently.
   Mrs. Dole will not be the only visitor from the nation's capital.
   Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine, plans to be on
hand and new Democratic National Committee Chairman Ronald Brown has
been invited to speak to the AFL-CIO's poltical committee.
   The planned unveiling of a key report, ``The Evolution of Work,''
however, has been delayed because of internal disagreements over
organizing tactics. Release of the report was to have been a
highlight of the meeting.
   Instead, Secretary-Treasurer Thomas Donahue will offer the
council a closed-door, verbal update on the status of the report,
now scheduled for release at the AFL-CIO's May convention in
Washington.
   Kirkland recently offered a brief sketch of the topics to be
covered in the report, including developing of new benefit programs,
such as cut-rate credit cards and legal services, designed to lure
into unions workers who now are covered by collective bargaining but
are not dues-paying members of unions.
   ``Some of the things we are trying may not work, but that tells
us something too,'' Kirkland said. ``Then we try something else.''
   Recent Labor Department figures show that while union membership
climbed slightly in 1988 the percentage of the workforce that is
unionized has dropped to about 16 percent _ meaning that labor is
not bringing in new members to match the rapid growth of the
workforce.
   To counter that, Kirkland said labor must do a better job of
organizing workers in service industries, the fastest-growing
segment of the economy.
   The first day of the meeting, Monday, will focus on domestic
policy, including the release by the Executive Council of its
positions on a number of major bills to be considered by the
Congress this year.
   That agenda includes an increased minimum wage, child care and
parental leave legislation as well as tighter restrictions on drug
testing and new protections for workers in nuclear facilities.
   Labor leaders also are lobbying heavily for restrictions on
leveraged buyouts, which they blame for massive layoffs because of
the debt assumed by most buyers in such transactions.
   Owen Bieber, president of the United Auto Workers, when asked
recently about labor's position on the buyouts, compared it to New
Deal restrictions on business.
   ``Franklin Roosevelt didn't put strict controls on business
activities during the Great Depression because he hated business,''
Bieber said. ``He did it because the business leaders of that time
completely defaulted on their responsibilities.''
   ``He said they had been indicted in the court of public
opinion,'' he said. ``Well, so have the Wall Street bloodsuckers of
the 1980s. And they should be driven from the temple.''
   While making its case in the national political debate, there
will be little to settle at this meeting concerning internal AFL-CIO
politics.
   Kirkland said last month that he will seek another two-year term
at the May convention, quashing rumors he might announce his
retirement, a move that would have set off jockeying among potential
challengers to Donahue, Kirkland's heir-apparent, and those with an
eye on Donahue's current post.
   ``I do not intend to quit,'' Kirkland said at a late January
meeting with reporters. ``The decision on my future in this
organization is in the best possible hands: God and the delegates.''
</TEXT>
