<FIRST>r i AM-Netherlands-ShipAccident     02-18 0197</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Netherlands-Ship Accident,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Danes Presumed Dead In Shipping Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOOK OF HOLLAND, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A British oil tanker collided
with a fishing boat on the North Sea early Saturday, and five Danish
fishermen were missing and presumed dead, a Dutch Coast Guard
spokesman said.
   Four Dutch rescue boats and a Dutch Navy helicopter found nothing
but wreckage, a small oil spill and an empty life raft of the
Danish-registered trawler Hanne Gasberg, according to spokesman,
Cees van Dijk.
   ``Chances of there being any survivors are virtually nil,'' Van
Dijk told The Associated Press.
   He added the search was called off six hours after the accident,
which occurred in high winds and pre-dawn darkness 23 miles off this
North Sea port.
   The 13,000-ton tanker British Beach simply ``overran'' the small
fishing trawler, Van Dijk said, adding that an investigation into
the cause of accident was to begin Sunday.
   The British-flagged tanker was en route from the port of Klaipeda
in Soviet Lithuania to Antwerp with a cargo of oil.
   The Danish ship was based in the port of Esbjerg, but left the
Dutch port of Scheveningen early Saturday on a fishing run, Van Dijk
said.
