<FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-Attack 3rdLd-Writethru   02-18 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Attack, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0581,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three U.S. Soldiers Hurt In Bus Blast</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with embassy saying device was
thrown at the bus, this was third attack in year and a half; picks up 4th
pvs, ``Sigmund said...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assailants on Saturday hurled a bomb
at the back of a bus carrying U.S. soldiers, wounding three of them
and two Honduran passersby, the U.S. Embassy and a nurse said.
   Anne M. Sigmund, director of public information for the embassy,
told The Associated Press by telephone, ``Two soldiers received
immediate medical attention and left the hospital, but the third one
is staying for observation.''
   The blast, which occurred about noon (1 p.m. EST) in Comayagua,
about 60 miles northwest of the capital, was the third attack
against U.S. soldiers in Honduras in the past year and a half.
   Sigmund said the soldiers were taken to the military hospital at
Enrique Soto Cano Air Base outside Comayagua. She did not describe
the extent of their injuries.
   There are about 1,200 U.S. soldiers stationed at the base.
   She said that the soldiers were injured when assailants hurled an
explosive device at the back of a rented bus in which 28 American
soldiers were returning to their base after a training visit to
Comayagua.
   Sigmund said it not not been determined what type of explosive
was thrown at the bus.
   ``There was an explosion, whose causes still are not known.
However, the act is being investigated by U.S. personnel and the
Honduran police,'' she added.
   The embassy spokeswoman said that no one had claimed immediate
reponsibility. ``For the moment, we are not giving out any more
information, which we will offer when the investigation is
concluded.''
   A nurse at Santa Teresa Hospital in Comayagua told The Associated
Press by telephone that two Honduran passersby also were being
treated for injuries in the attack.
   The nurse, who did not give her name, said that both men were
treated at the hospital. ``They suffered light injuries and are
staying for observation,'' she said.
   Johnny Banegas, announcer for a radio station in Comayagua, said,
``I saw that a device exploded in the back of the bus, affecting two
nearby buildings, one a hotel and the other a school.''
   ``The back part of the vehicle was practically destroyed,'' he
said.
   Carlos Jimenez, another witness, told reporters, ``A little after
the explosion, various American (military) police arrived on the
scene with dogs trained in the detection of explosives.''
   He added, ``It all happened so fast. The soldiers, most of them,
got out of the bus. I saw one of them being carried by his
companions because he apparently had leg injuries.''
   This was the third terrorist attack against U.S. soldiers, who
have been conducting maneuvers in Honduras since 1982. Leftist
groups have protested the maneuvers.
   On Aug. 7, 1987, a bomb injured six American soldiers and six
Honduran civilians in a Comayagua restaurant.
   On Feb. 1, seven vehicles carrying more than 30 American soldiers
was attacked by unidentified gunmen in northern Yoro province, but
no one was injured.
</TEXT>
