<HEAD>Report: U.S. Jets Narrowly Missed Airliners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD time element. Pickup 4th graf ``As
if...''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six U.S. warplanes on a low-level
training flight changed course without warning and flew dangerously
close to six passenger jets, a magazine reported Saturday.
   Der Spiegel also reported that U.S. intelligence agents are
eavesdropping on European phone calls.
   The Hamburg-based newsmagazine said the F-16 fighter planes based
at the U.S. Air Force headquarters at Ramstein flew into heavy fog
Tuesday and pulled into a steep climb, narrowly missing six
airliners in a holding pattern waiting to land at Frankfurt Airport.
   ``As if they were alone in the air, they switched their radio
signals to `Code 77' (emergency) and went into a steep climb,'' Der
Spiegel said.
   Der Spiegel said the fighters came within yards of the airliners.
   Spokesmen for the U.S. Air Force in Ramstein could not be reached
for comment Saturday night.
   The magazine quoted a civilian air traffic controller as saying:
``They haven't learned anything from Remscheid.''
   A U.S. Air Force warplane in December crashed into a residential
area of the central city of Remscheid, killing the pilot and five
people on the ground.
   U.S. officials are under growing pressure to reduce military
training flights after a series of plane crashes that killed more
than 100 people last year.
   The magazine also reported that the National Security Agency had
set up a facility in Frankfurt designed not only to pick up military
signals from the Warsaw Pact, but also to eavesdrop at will on
thousands of private phone calls in West Germany and Europe.
   The magazine said the agency also had listening posts at three
other locations in West Germany.
   Spiegel said that West German intelligence agencies often receive
information from the U.S. listening posts to help them kept track of
extremist activities in the country.
