<FIRST>u a AM-FairMelee     02-18 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fair Melee,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gang Of 200 Youths Harass Fair Goers; 60 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rampage by more than 200 youths who stole
belongings from people at a ``Midnight Madness'' fair ended early
Saturday after five hours of fighting that injured about 60 people,
authorities said.
   Of the 60 people hurt, four were sheriff's deputies, authorities
said. Forty people required hospital treatment for injuries ranging
from cuts and bruises to broken bones. One beaten man had to be
revived by officers and another man required 30 stitches to close a
deep cut to his back, police said.
   The youths, who in seven or eight loosely organized groups,
started ``sucker punching'' and stealing belongings from people at
the Florida State Fair just after 10:30 p.m. Friday, said Sgt.
Kenneth Akins of the Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office.
   Authorities weren't able to bring the situation under control
until about 4 a.m., Akins said.
   ``This is probably the worst event that I have ever worked in the
sheriff's office in 12 years,'' said Akins, commander of the
sheriff's special crowd-control unit.
   Deputies arrested about 12 people, most of them juveniles, the
officer said.
   About 30,000 people attended the fair's special discount event
called ``Midnight Madness.'' Organizers had only expected 10,000 to
12,000.
   There were no reports of violence Saturday night at the fair,
which was scheduled to close at midnight. The fair, billed as having
the Southeast's largest midway, began Feb. 8 and ends Sunday night.
