<HEAD>Newspaper Chief Offers Reward To `Civilize' Khomeini</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspaper magnate Robert Maxwell has pledged $10.6
million to anyone who can ``civilize'' Iranian ruler Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, one of his newspapers announced Sunday.
   The People, a London weekly tabloid, said the money would be paid
to anyone who can persuade the Moslem leader to repent ``his wicked
ways'' by persuading him to publicly recite the sixth and ninth of
the Ten Commandments: ``Thou shalt not kill'' and ``Thou shall not
bear false witness.''
   Maxwell's offer doubles the price put on the head of British
writer Salman Rushdie by Iranian religious leaders.
   They did so after Khomeini said Tuesday that Rushdie's novel
``The Satanic Verses'' was an insult to ``Islamic sanctity'' and
zealous Moislems should execute him and those closely connected with
the book's publication.
   Rushdie has since disappeared from view and has been reported in
hiding with an armed police guard.
