<FIRST>u i AM-Malaysia-Crash 3rdLd-Writethru a0618 02-18 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Malaysia-Crash, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0618,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Commercial Cargo Plane Crashes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with four dead, all identified as Americans,
and more details of crash, including origin and witness report; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Flying Tigers cargo plane slammed
into the hilly jungle outside the capital Sunday and burst into
flames, killing all four people on board, authorities said. The dead
were identified as U.S. citizens.
   The Boeing 747 operated by the Los Angeles-based air freight
company was to land at Subang International Airport outside Kuala
Lumpur when it disappeared from radar, Civil Aviation Department
officials said.
   Four crew members were the only people on board and all four
killed, said Nordin Saad, air traffic control director for the Civil
Aviation Department.
   The plane, which took off from Singapore, crashed at 6:36 a.m.
(5:36 p.m. EST), he said.
   He said the bodies were recovered but the identities were being
withheld pending notification of relatives.
   U.S. Embassy spokeswoman Meg Gillroy said in a statement that all
four crew members were U.S. citizens.
   Other Civil Aviation officials, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said the flight data recorder had been recovered, but no
cause of the crash was readily apparent.
   The jumbo jet crashed about nine miles from the airport in the
dense, hilly jungle. Aviation officials said the aircraft left
Singapore with a load of freight, including mail and clothing.
   The crash site is slightly more than four miles away from the
nearest residential area.
   Chooi Joon Hoong, 48, told reporters that he was out at his fruit
orchard at the foot of the hills when he heard a loud explosion and
then smoke from the hills.
</TEXT>
