<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     02-18 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0365</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Begins Talks With Opposition Leaders</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday began talks
with opposition to seek solutions to the political problems plaguing
the country.
   Carlos Huembes, president of the opposition Nicarguan Workers
Central and the Nicaraguan Democratic Coordinate, met Thursday with
Vice President Sergio Ramirez.
   The Sandinista government did not offer an official version of
the Friday meeting with opposition leaders. Though no agreement was
reached, the possibility of new talks remains open, Huembes said.
   President Daniel Ortega, during a summit of Central American
presidents this week, promised to ``develop a process of
democratization and national reconciliation'' in the country.
   At the end of the summit held Monday and Tuesday in El Salvador,
Ortega also promised to hold presidential, legislative and municipal
elections by February and to allow the opposition to help organize
them.
   The balloting had been scheduled for November 1990.
   A summit agreement signed by Ortega and the presidents of El
Salvador Guatemala, Honduras and Costa Rica also calls for
disbanding the Nicaraguan rebels known as the Contras, most of whom
are encamped in nearby Honduras.
   Rebel leaders have said they have felt abandoned by the United
States, which had supported their seven-year fight to oust the
leftist government.
   Despite vows to fight on, the Contras ran out of ammunition and
moved into border camps after Congress suspended military aid a year
ago. On March 23, they signed a preliminary cease-fire accord with
the Sandinistas.
   Huembes told journalists on Friday that the vice president told
him and other opposition leaders that ``all of us Nicaraguans must
resolve the problem, without abandoning our own principles.''
   Huembes said he told Ramirez that true political pluralism must
be created and called for an end to what he described as ``the
blackmail, coersion and buying and selling'' among political parties
that make up the National Assembly.
   He said he told the vice president that if the current political
situation continues ``thousands upon thousands of Nicaraguans will
reclaim their rights.''
   Huembes was accompanied during the meeting by Roger Guevara, the
coordinate secretary general.
</TEXT>
