<FIRST>a f BC-RadioactivePipe Adv20   02-18 0540</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Radioactive Pipe, Adv 20,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Feb. 20.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Radioactive Pipe Said To Pose Little Threat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana has adopted temporary rules to
safely handle radium-contaminated pipe from oilfields, although the
state's environmental chief says the tubing appears to pose almost
no public threat.
   The radium, which is leached from uranium and thorium found in
deep geological formations, is brought to the surface with oilfield
brine and tends to concentrate in the scaly residue that forms
inside pipe.
   Paul Templet, secretary of the Department of Environmental
Quality, said possible health problems are limited mostly to yard
workers who cut up and process them for other uses, such as
parking-lot barriers and cattle pens.
   ``The problem is that the dust can fall out of the pipes and then
you can get a hot spot in the yard,'' Templet said. ``It's really
not a problem if you get it on your skin, but if you get it in your
lungs, then you have a problem.''
   Earlier this month the department enacted temporary rules
concerning how the pipe is handled. The rules require companies with
contaminated pipe to inform the agency and prohibit the transfer of
land for unrestricted use where topsoil radium is above a certain
level.
   The agency said its major concerns were the safety of workers who
cut or clean the pipe and the contamination of soil in pipeyards,
which might cause problems with radon gas if buildings were erected
on the sites.
   Templet said the potential problem with contaminated pipes is
``peanuts'' for oil field workers and the threat to the general
public appears to be sharply limited since radium radiation is
non-penetrating.
   The environmental department imposed the new rules under
``emergency'' procedures that allow the the regulations to take
effect before the end of a 120-day period required by state law.
   Oil industry officials blamed news of the regulations as one
contributor to a rise in crude oil prices last Wednesday. They said
the reports incited rumors that oil and gas from Louisiana was
contaminated and unsellable.
   ``The emergency rules merely deal with pipe that may have
(radium-contaminated) scale in them,'' Templet said.
   Templet said the temporary rules will allow the department to
stop pipeyards from unloading pipe before the new regulations take
effect.
   ``If we went with normal procedures, they (pipe yards) could stop
moving it out. They can't now and we'll go through normal
(rule-making) procedures,'' to make the regulations permanent, he
said.
   The state has no statistics on how many yards are handling the
pipes and the new rules should help authorities find exact numbers,
Templet said.
   Knowledge of the problem, he said, has been limited mostly to
industry people familiar with radiation control. A national study
group has been working for several years to draw up recommendations
to handle the pipe, he said.
   The department began studying the issue about six months ago
after receiving reports from metal scrap yards that routinely
monitor incoming pipe for radiation, Templet said.
   In the future, contaminated pipe probably will be stored like
other low-radiation hazards because the process of cleaning out the
scale is prohibitively expensive, Templet said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday, Feb. 20.</NOTE>
